<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="458" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,427,1318]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,428,454]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Collett, R." box="[277,435,427,454]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" pagination="353 - 357" refId="ref13851" refString="Collett, R. (1898) On some pigeons and parrots from North and Northwest Australia. Proceedings of the General Meetings for Scientific Business of the Zoological Society of London, 1898, 353 - 357. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1898. tb 03152. x" type="journal article" year="1898">Collett (1898)</bibRefCitation>
based the original description on two birds, a male and a female collected by Knut Dahl, without specifying any one of them as the 
<typeStatus box="[622,724,463,489]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">holotype</typeStatus>
. The other specimen was sent to the BMNH (
<bibRefCitation author="Sharpe, R. B." box="[1226,1371,463,489]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" pagination="79 - 515" refId="ref16564" refString="Sharpe, R. B. (1906) 3. Birds. In: The history of the collections contained in the Natural History Departments of the British Museum. Vol. II. Separate historical accounts of the several collections included in the Department of Zoology. Trustees of the British Museum, London, pp. 79 - 515." type="book chapter" year="1906">Sharpe 1906</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Warren, R. L. M." pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref16906" refString="Warren, R. L. M. (1966) Type-specimens of birds in the British Museum (Natural History). Vol. 1. Non-Passerines. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 320 pp." type="book" year="1966">Warren 1966</bibRefCitation>
), where it is currently catalogued as NHMUK 1898.10.10.2 (
<bibRefCitation author="Natural History Museum" box="[953,1320,499,526]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref15777" refString="Natural History Museum (2014 b) Dataset: Collection specimens. Resource: Specimens. Specimen 1898.10. 10.2, Natural History Museum Data Portal (data. nhm. ac. uk). Available from: https: // data. nhm. ac. uk / object / 74 fe 774 f- 0 f 7 c- 4784 - 9213 - 49 d 4 606968 f 7 / 1642550400000 (accessed 14 March 2022)" type="url" year="2014">Natural History Museum 2014b</bibRefCitation>
; Hein van Grouw, pers. comm.). Based on a list of specimens collected by Dahl during his 
<collectingCountry box="[1040,1143,535,561]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Australia</collectingCountry>
expedition (unpublished), it is evident that the original collector’s number of the NHMUK specimen must be 1248.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,427,1318]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">
The original label, written by the collector, is present at the base of the stand (
<figureCitation box="[1088,1203,607,634]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1763,1787]" captionTargetBox="[175,1413,868,1732]" captionTargetId="figure-168@6.[168,1420,858,1738]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Labels of type specimens in the NHMO Bird Collection described by R. Collett. a) Petrophassa rufipennis NHMO- BI-77947 (collector’s label); b) Ptilopus (Leucotreron) alligator NHMO-BI-77948 (collector’s label); c) Psephotus dissimilis NHMO-BI-64125 (collector’s label); d) Psephotus dissimilis NHMO-BI-64125 (NHMO label); e) Psephotus dissimilis NHMO- BI-85843 (collector’s label)." pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Figure 2b</figureCitation>
). The species is also here referred to simply as 
<emphasis box="[444,566,643,669]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">‘Columba’</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,427,1318]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">
Collett placed this new taxon in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[720,856,680,705]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ptilopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Leucotreron">
<emphasis box="[720,856,680,705]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Leucotreron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and used the spelling 
<taxonomicName box="[1110,1203,679,705]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ptilopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1110,1203,679,705]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Ptilopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the genus, while the original spelling was 
<taxonomicName authority="(Swainson 1825)" baseAuthorityName="Swainson" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[436,754,715,742]" class="Aves" family="Columbidae" genus="Ptilinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Columbiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[436,551,715,741]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Ptilinopus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Swainson, W." box="[567,745,715,742]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" pagination="463 - 484" refId="ref16683" refString="Swainson, W. (1825) On the characters and natural affinities of several new birds from Australasia; including some observations on the Columbidae. The Zoological Journal, 1 (4), 463 - 484." type="journal article" year="1825">Swainson 1825</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The form 
<taxonomicName box="[879,972,715,741]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ptilopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[879,972,715,741]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Ptilopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was apparently introduced by 
<bibRefCitation author="Strickland, H. E." pageId="7" pageNumber="458" pagination="26 - 41" refId="ref16627" refString="Strickland, H. E. (1841) Commentary on Mr. G. R. Gray's ' Genera of birds, ' 1840. The Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 1, 7 (41), 26 - 41. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03745484109442660" type="journal article" year="1841">Strickland (1841</bibRefCitation>
: p. 36), posing the question 
<emphasis box="[547,679,751,777]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">‘Should not</emphasis>
Ptilonopus [sic] 
<emphasis box="[875,989,751,777]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">be written</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[998,1090,751,777]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ptilopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ptilopus</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1090,1104,752,778]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">?</emphasis>
’, and in the period to follow this seemed to be the favoured spelling of the genus (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bonaparte, C. L." box="[813,996,787,814]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref13713" refString="Bonaparte, C. L. (1857) Conspectus generum avium. Vol. 2. E. J. Brill, Leyden, 232 pp." type="book" year="1857">Bonaparte 1857</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rowley, G. D." box="[1009,1164,787,814]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref16144" refString="Rowley, G. D. (1877) On the genus Ptilopus. In: Rowley, G. D. (Ed.), Ornithological Miscellany. Vol. 2. Trubner and Co., London, pp. 337 - 351." type="book" year="1877">Rowley 1877</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Elliot, D. G." box="[1177,1308,787,814]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" pagination="500 - 575" refId="ref14276" refString="Elliot, D. G. (1878) On the fruit-pigeons of the genus Ptilopus. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1878, 500 - 575. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1878. tb 07987. x" type="journal article" year="1878">Elliot 1878</bibRefCitation>
). Currently the original spelling is again used by all the major taxonomic lists, including the IOC World Bird List (
<bibRefCitation author="Gill, F. &amp; Donsker, D. &amp; Rasmussen, P." pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref14326" refString="Gill, F., Donsker, D. &amp; Rasmussen, P. (2022) IOC World Bird List (v 12.1). Available from: http: // www. worldbirdnames. org / (accessed 28 March 2022) https: // doi. org / 10.14344 / IOC. ML. 12.1" type="url" year="2022">
Gill 
<emphasis box="[1379,1437,823,849]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName box="[276,412,860,885]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ptilopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Leucotreron">
<emphasis box="[276,412,860,885]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Leucotreron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is no longer recognized as a subgenus. According to the Code (
<bibRefCitation author="International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref14975" refString="International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature (1999) International code of zoological nomenclature. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London, 306 pp." type="book" year="1999">International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature 1999</bibRefCitation>
) these changes in the spelling of the genus name (Article 51.3.1) and rank (Article 51.3.2) do not warrant use of parentheses around the original author name.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,427,1318]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">
For the NHMUK specimen, slightly different coordinates are provided for the South 
<taxonomicName authority="River" authorityName="River" box="[1188,1362,967,993]" class="Aves" family="Columbidae" genus="Ptilinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Columbiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alligator">Alligator River</taxonomicName>
locality (
<bibRefCitation author="Warren, R. L. M." box="[197,348,1003,1030]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref16906" refString="Warren, R. L. M. (1966) Type-specimens of birds in the British Museum (Natural History). Vol. 1. Non-Passerines. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 320 pp." type="book" year="1966">Warren 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schodde, R. &amp; Mason, I. J." box="[361,640,1003,1030]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref16524" refString="Schodde, R. &amp; Mason, I. J. (1997) Zoological Catalogue of Australia. Aves (Columbidae to Coraciidae). Vol. 37.2. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, xiii + 440 pp." type="book" year="1997">Schodde &amp; Mason 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Natural History Museum" box="[654,1020,1003,1030]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref15777" refString="Natural History Museum (2014 b) Dataset: Collection specimens. Resource: Specimens. Specimen 1898.10. 10.2, Natural History Museum Data Portal (data. nhm. ac. uk). Available from: https: // data. nhm. ac. uk / object / 74 fe 774 f- 0 f 7 c- 4784 - 9213 - 49 d 4 606968 f 7 / 1642550400000 (accessed 14 March 2022)" type="url" year="2014">Natural History Museum 2014b</bibRefCitation>
); 
<geoCoordinate box="[1041,1152,1004,1030]" degrees="13" direction="south" minutes="30" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" precision="925" value="-13.5">13° 30`S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1166,1291,1003,1030]" degrees="132" direction="east" minutes="50" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" precision="925" value="132.83333">132° 50`E</geoCoordinate>
= 
<geoCoordinate box="[1324,1437,1003,1030]" degrees="13.500" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" precision="55" value="-13.5">13.500° S</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[151,278,1040,1066]" degrees="132.833" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" precision="55" value="132.833">132.833° E</geoCoordinate>
, i.e. ca. 
<quantity box="[367,436,1039,1066]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" unit="km" value="29.0">29 km</quantity>
further east than those provided above. While the location provided in the current publication is based on a detailed study of the travelogue of the collector (
<bibRefCitation author="Dahl, K." box="[891,1013,1075,1102]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref13909" refString="Dahl, K. (1898) Reiser i Nord-Vest-Australien. Alb. Cammermeyers Forlag, Kristiania, 462 pp." type="book" year="1898">Dahl 1898</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dahl, K." box="[1024,1084,1075,1102]" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" refId="ref13953" refString="Dahl, K. (1926) In savage Australia. An account of a hunting and collecting expedition to Arnhem Land and Dampier Land. Philip Allan, London, 326 pp." type="book" year="1926">1926</bibRefCitation>
), as well as his field diaries and letters to Collett, it has not been possible to find any documented source of the coordinates given in the NHMUK records. It is therefore assumed that they are added simply on the basis of the rather wide-ranging locality name (no coordinates are present, neither in the register book nor on any of the labels of the specimen; Hein van Grouw, pers. comm.). As Dahl in a letter to Collett stated that they had been travelling in the mountains between the Mary and South 
<taxonomicName authority="Rivers" authorityName="Rivers" box="[221,405,1255,1281]" class="Aves" family="Columbidae" genus="Ptilinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Columbiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="458" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alligator">Alligator Rivers</taxonomicName>
, we consider the coordinates presented here to be the more likely of the two sets (though still subject to the cautionary note provided in the 
<emphasis box="[664,748,1292,1317]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="458">Format</emphasis>
section above).
</paragraph>
